The only large painting I have in my studio right now.
For some reason, summer is not a good time for painting large. That’s more of a long winter evenings kind of work.

Right now, my palette is dry and my fingernails are permanently green from picking pine cones. But I have a lot of works to share with you from my winter painting marathon. 

Somehow painting became seasonal.

I’d like to paint on something that moves ever so slightly with the wind. Something like a field of young spring grass.
I had a dream about it once, it was beautiful.

Trying to find balance between the pressure of social media and the slowness of creative process.

Sparkles ✨

The colors of cold water.

“Cold” in a good way. 

Recently, I was made aware that this requires clarification.
Luckily, these lakes are never warm. If they were, algae would take over, rocks would turn muddy green, and my paintings would look very different.

“The Great Outdoors” show opening is tonight! These paintings will be on display at @arcadiagallery until October 29th. Come say hi if you are in the area!

For inquiries, please contact info@arcadiacontemporary.com

“Earendel”
The farthest star ever discovered.
It appears on a string of light created by gravitational lensing from the massive galaxy cluster. 
And to me it looks so similar to our morning sun reflected on a crushing wave’s face.
Dancing around the spot in front of my easel where I usually stand, because NO ONE is allowed to touch Queen Sophie when she’s comfortable🐶

Today, I just want to thank you for being here! Your support means the world to me🤍

When early astronomers were mapping the moon, they assumed that the darker areas on its surface were oceans, seas and lakes, and named them accordingly. 

Now we know those are not bodies of water.

But I wonder how would Sea of Serenity look like if it existed?

A little moon drop

“Stardust”

A little more abstract than most of my paintings. 
I finished it back in 2019. And only now, finally, I’m working on the rest of the series. 

That’s one way to test an idea: let it simmer for 5 years and see if it still wants to come out after that.
It has become a tradition to start a new year with several smaller paintings. Sometimes I use them later for a larger work. But mostly this is just a way for me to try out different ideas.
About those small painting collections I mentioned yesterday: here’s one from 2021.
These might be the colors of my next large painting
Loving these colors🤍
